-- South African Stocks Fall for Second Day; Adcock Ingram, BHP, DRDGold Move
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-12-10T08:17:19Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-10/south-african-stocks-adcock-ingram-bhp-drdgold-pioneer-food.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  fell for a second day, dropping 33.91, or 0.1
percent, to 31,583.75 as at 10:16 a.m. in Johannesburg. The
following were among the most active stocks in the South African
market today.  Adcock Ingram Holdings Ltd.  (AIP SJ), South Africa’s
largest over-the-counter drug-maker, declined 2 rand, or 3
percent, to 64.5 rand. The drug-maker said South Africa’s
Medicines Control Council has withdrawn medicines containing
dextropropoxyphene. Adcock has three products containing
dextropropoxyphene, and had combined sales of 200 million rand
in fiscal 2010, Adcock said.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, snapped two days of losses, increasing 2.1 rand, or 0.8
percent, to 268.93 rand. The company has raised its wage offer
for striking workers at the Hillside aluminum smelter in South
Africa to 8.5 percent, Reuters reported, citing a National Union
of Metalworkers spokesman.  DRDGold Ltd.  (DRD SJ), a gold mining company, advanced for
the second day in three, adding 5 cents, or 1.5 percent, to 3.5
rand. DRDGold said it expects to make an average of 10,000 rand
more per kilogram of gold sold in the December quarter than the
288,000 rand it received in the previous quarter.  To contact the reporter on this story:
